{
  "doc_id": "8109",
  "text": "Evidence of windstorm damages to forest ecosystems is widely reported for North America [CITATION_1] , Peterson 2000 and Tropics [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , while reports for Europe [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and the Mediterranean region are more rare, as related to the lower occurrence and intensity of extreme events. However, windstorm frequency and impact in Mediterranean forests have been increasing since the midtwentieth century, putatively due to climate change and forest management activities [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Such trend is expected to increase in the near future, possibly leading to a severe loss in forest structure, functioning and economic value [CITATION_8] ). In addition, the impact of windstorm on forest ecosystems can interact with anthropogenic activities. In the Mediterranean basin, urbanization dramatically increased in the last decades [CITATION_9] . Urban and suburban forests are characterized by a specific ecology, being negatively affected by the surrounding urban landscape that create habitat fragmentation, induce community homogenization and so promote the spread of non-native species [CITATION_10] .",
